<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910207-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>910207-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Burlington Northern Inc.:   Company Sets $46 Million   To Settle Labor Dispute</HL><DATE>02/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BNI LABOR</CO><IN>RAILROADS (RAI)</IN><LP>   Burlington Northern Inc. said it plans to set aside about$46 million in its first quarter to cover part of theanticipated cost of settling a labor dispute.   The Fort Worth, Texas, railroad company's unions have beenworking without a health and welfare agreement since 1984 anda wage agreement since 1988. A presidential emergency boardappointed to review the dispute recommended last month thateligible union members receive a 3% wage increase by July 1,and a one-time signing bonus of $2,000 an employee at thetime of the settlement.</LP><TEXT>   The company accrued $24 million in the fourth quarter inanticipation of a settlement that would include someretroactive payment. The latest accrual is for costs of theone-time signing bonus and benefits. It also said that if anagreement is not reached by July 1, it would begin accruingfor the 3% wage increases proposed in the emergency board'sreport.   It remains unclear whether the dispute will be settledthrough negotiations or congressional action, or whether theunions will strike. Burlington Northern said a federallyordered cooling-off period of 30 days expires next Thursday,but federal mediators are asking for a further 30 days.</TEXT></DOC>